ve enough chalk, so they will have to replace it.\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `chalk.length == n`\n\n- `1 <= n <= 10⁵`\n\n- `1 <= chalk[i] <= 10⁵`\n\n- `1 <= k <= 10⁹`","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/find-the-student-that-will-replace-the-chalk/","problemName":"Find the Student that Will Replace the Chalk","problemNumber":1894,"problemSlug":"find-the-student-that-will-replace-the-chalk","schemaVersion":2,"sequenceIndex":1894,"solutionApproaches":[]},{"assets":[{"assetIndex":0,"bytes":20183,"contentType":"image/jpeg","localPath":"leetcode_seed/assets/problems/1895-largest-magic-square/1895-magicsquare-grid.jpg","originalUrl":"../../../images/1895-magicsquare-grid.jpg","sha256":"786f23b0238198b75118665b91f8e42af1ea739a111079134087106b51e63ee0"},{"assetIndex":1,"bytes":12862,"contentType":"image/jpeg","localPath":"leetcode_seed/assets/problems/1895-largest-magic-square/1895-magicsquare2-grid.jpg","originalUrl":"../../../images/1895-magicsquare2-grid.jpg","sha256":"3382cc54aaa59e60016e59006cdc50efd19409d7586df7061504f839c958d1a2"}],"categories":["Array","Matrix","Prefix Sum"],"constraintBlocks":[],"contentBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"A `k x k` **magic square** is a `k x k` grid filled with integers such that every row sum, every column sum, and both diagonal sums are **all equal**. The integers in the magic square **do not have to be distinct**. Every `1 x 1` grid is trivially a **magic square**.\n\nGiven an `m x n` integer `grid`, return *the **size** (i.e., the side length *`k`*) of the **largest magic square** that can be found within this grid*.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"alt":"Problem image","contentType":"image/jpeg","localPath":"leetcode_seed/assets/problems/1895-largest-magic-square/1895-magicsquare-grid.jpg","sequence":1,"sha256":"786f23b0238198b75118665b91f8e42af1ea739a111079134087106b51e63ee0","type":"image"},{"sequence":2,"text":"Input: grid = [[7,1,4,5,6],[2,5,1,6,4],[1,5,4,3,2],[1,2,7,3,4]]\nOutput: 3\nExplanation: The largest magic square has a size of 3.\nEvery row sum, column sum, and diagonal sum of this magic square is equal to 12.\n- Row sums: 5+1+6 = 5+4+3 = 2+7+3 = 12\n- Column sums: 5+5+2 = 1+4+7 = 6+3+3 = 12\n- Diagonal sums: 5+4+3 = 6+4+2 = 12","type":"code"},{"sequence":3,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"alt":"Problem image","contentType":"image/jpeg","localPath":"leetcode_seed/assets/problems/1895-largest-magic-square/1895-magicsquare2-grid.jpg","sequence":4,"sha256":"3382cc54aaa59e60016e59006cdc50efd19409d7586df7061504f839c958d1a2","type":"image"},{"sequence":5,"text":"Input: grid = [[5,1,3,1],[9,3,3,1],[1,3,3,8]]\nOutput: 2","type":"code"},{"sequence":6,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `m == grid.length`\n\n- `n == grid[i].length`\n\n- `1 <= m, n <= 50`\n\n- `1 <= grid[i][j] <= 10⁶`","type":"text"}],"contentHtml":"","contentHtmlLocal":"","databaseEntry":{"categories":["Array","Matrix","Prefix Sum"],"createdAt":0,"difficulty":"Medium","lastRevisionAt":0,"problem":"A `k x k` **magic square** is a `k x k` grid filled with integers such that every row sum, every column sum, and both diagonal sums are **all equal**. The integers in the magic square **do not have to be distinct**. Every `1 x 1` grid is trivially a **magic square**.\n\nGiven an `m x n` integer `grid`, return *the **size** (i.e., the side length *`k`*) of the **largest magic square** that can be found within this grid*.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\n[[img:leetcode_seed/assets/problems/1895-largest-magic-square/1895-magicsquare-grid.jpg]]\n\nInput: grid = [[7,1,4,5,6],[2,5,1,6,4],[1,5,4,3,2],[1,2,7,3,4]]\nOutput: 3\nExplanation: The largest magic square has a size of 3.\nEvery row sum, column sum, and diagonal sum of this magic square is equal to 12.\n- Row sums: 5+1+6 = 5+4+3 = 2+7+3 = 12\n- Column sums: 5+5+2 = 1+4+7 = 6+3+3 = 12\n- Diagonal sums: 5+4+3 = 6+4+2 = 12\n\n**Example 2:**\n\n[[img:leetcode_seed/assets/problems/1895-largest-magic-square/1895-magicsquare2-grid.jpg]]\n\nInput: grid = [[5,1,3,1],[9,3,3,1],[1,3,3,8]]\